A piggyback ack is an acknowledgment to a received packet that is sent along in an outgoing data packet to the remote computer. If no outgoing packet is sent within the timeout period, then an ack packet is sent and this counter is incremented.

children.name: ntsystemContextSwitchesPerSec
children.description: Context Switches/sec is the rate of switches from one thread to another. Thread switches can occur either inside of a single process or across processes. A thread switch may be caused either by one thread asking another for information, or by a thread being preempted by another, higher priority thread becoming ready to run. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of User and Privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of an application may appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the Privileged Time in the application. Switching to the subsystem process causes one Context Switch in the application thread. Switching back causes another Context Switch in the subsystem thread.

children.name: ntsystemSystemCallsPerSec
children.description: Systems Calls/sec is the frequency of calls to Windows NT system service routines. These routines perform all of the basic scheduling and synchronization of activities on the computer, and provide access to non-graphical devices, memory management, and name space management.

children.name: ntsystemPercentTotalProcessorTime
children.description: The % Total Processor Time is the average percentage of time that all the processors on the system are busy executing non-idle threads. On a multi-processor system, if all processors are always busy this is 100%, if all processors are 50% busy this is 50% and if 1/4th of the processors are 100% busy this is 25%. It can be viewed as the fraction of the time spent doing useful work. Each processor is assigned an Idle thread in the Idle process which consumes those unproductive processor cycles not used by any other threads.

children.name: ntsystemPercentTotalUserTime
children.description: The % Total User Time is the average percentage of time spent in User mode by all processors. On a multi-processor system, if all processors are always in User mode this is 100%, if all processors are 50% in User mode this is 50% and if 1/4th of the processors are in User mode this is 25%. Applications execute in User Mode, as do subsystems like the window manager and the graphics engine. Code executing in User Mode cannot damage the integrity of the Windows NT Executive, Kernel, and device drivers. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of User and Privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of an application may appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the Privileged Time in the application process.

children.name: ntsystemPercentTotalPrivilegedTime
children.description: The % Total Privileged Time is the average percentage of time spent in Privileged mode by all processors. On a multi-processor system, if all processors are always in Privileged mode this is 100%, and if 1/4th of the processors are in Privileged mode this is 25%. When a Windows NT system service is called, the service will often run in Privileged Mode in order to gain access to system-private data. Such data is protected from access by threads executing in User Mode. Calls to the system may be explicit, or they may be implicit such as when a page fault or an interrupt occurs. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of User and Privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of an application may appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the Privileged Time in the application process.

children.name: ntsystemTotalInterruptsPerSec
children.description: Total Interrupts/sec is the rate the computer is receiving and servicing hardware interrupts. Some devices that may generate interrupts are the system timer, the mouse, data communication lines, network interface cards and other peripheral devices. This counter provides an indication of how busy these devices are on a computer-wide basis. See also Processor:Interrupts/sec.

children.name: ntsystemFileDataOperationsPerSec

children.name: ntsystemProcessorQueueLength
children.description: Processor Queue Length is the instantaneous length of the processor queue in units of threads. This counter is always 0 unless you are also monitoring a thread counter. All processors use a single queue in which threads wait for processor cycles. This length does not include the threads that are currently executing. A sustained processor queue length greater than two generally indicates processor congestion. This is an instantaneous count, not an average over the time interval.

children.name: webserviceCurrentNonAnonymousUsers
children.description: Current NonAnonymous Users is the number of users who currently have a non-anonymous connection using the Web service.

children.name: webserviceTotalAnonymousUsers
children.description: Total Anonymous Users is the total number of users who established an anonymous connection with the Web service (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceAnonymousUsersPerSec
children.description: The rate users are making anonymous connections using the Web service.

children.name: webserviceTotalNonAnonymousUsers
children.description: Total NonAnonymous Users is the total number of users who established a non-anonymous connection with the Web service (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceNonAnonymousUsersPerSec
children.description: The rate users are making non-anonymous connections using the Web service.

children.name: webserviceMaximumAnonymousUsers
children.description: Maximum Anonymous Users is the maximum number of users who established concurrent anonymous connections using the Web service (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceMaximumNonAnonymousUsers
children.description: Maximum NonAnonymous Users is the maximum number of users who established concurrent non-anonymous connections using the Web service (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceCurrentConnections
children.description: Current Connections is the current number of connections established with the Web service.

children.name: webserviceMaximumConnections
children.description: Maximum Connections is the maximum number of simultaneous connections established with the Web service.

children.name: webserviceTotalConnectionAttempts
children.description: Total Connection Attempts is the number of connections that have been attempted using the Web service (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceConnectionAttemptsPerSec
children.description: The rate that connections using the Web service are being attempted.

children.name: webserviceTotalLogonAttempts
children.description: Total Logon Attempts is the number of logons that have been attempted using the Web service (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceLogonAttemptsPerSec
children.description: The rate that logons using the Web service are being attempted.

children.name: webserviceTotalGetRequests
children.description: Total Get Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the GET method (counted since service startup). Get requests are generally used for basic file retrievals or image maps, though they can be used with forms.

children.name: webserviceGetRequestsPerSec
children.description: The rate HTTP requests using the GET method are made. Get requests are generally used for basic file retrievals or image maps, though they can be used with forms.

children.name: webserviceTotalPostRequests
children.description: Total Post Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the POST method (counted since service startup). Post requests are generally used for forms or gateway requests.

children.name: webservicePostRequestsPerSec
children.description: The rate HTTP requests using the POST method are made. Post requests are generally used for forms or gateway requests.

children.name: webserviceTotalHeadRequests
children.description: Total Head Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the HEAD method (counted since service startup). Head requests generally indicate a client is querying the state of a document they already have to see if it needs to be refreshed.

children.name: webserviceHeadRequestsPerSec
children.description: The rate HTTP requests using the HEAD method are made. Head requests generally indicate a client is querying the state of a document they already have to see if it needs to be refreshed.

children.name: webserviceTotalPutRequests
children.description: Total Put Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the PUT method (counted since service startup).

children.name: webservicePutRequestsPerSec
children.description: The rate HTTP requests using the PUT method are made.

children.name: webserviceTotalDeleteRequests
children.description: Total Delete Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the DELETE method (counted since service startup). Delete requests are generally used for file removals.

children.name: webserviceDeleteRequestsPerSec
children.description: The rate HTTP requests using the DELETE method are made. Delete requests are generally used for file removals.

children.name: webserviceTotalTraceRequests
children.description: Total Trace Requests is the number of HTTP requests using the TRACE method (counted since service startup). Trace requests allow the client to see what is being received at the end of the request chain and use the information for diagnostic purposes.

children.name: webserviceSystemCodeResidentBytes
children.description: System Code Resident Bytes

children.name: webserviceTotalOtherRequestMethods
children.description: Total Other Request Methods is the number of HTTP requests that are not GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, TRACE or HEAD methods (counted since service startup). These may include LINK or other methods supported by gateway applications.

children.name: webserviceOtherRequestMethodsPerSec
children.description: The rate HTTP requests are made that do not use the GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, TRACE or HEAD methods. These may include LINK or other methods supported by gateway applications.

children.name: webserviceTotalMethodRequests
children.description: Total Method Requests is the number of HTTP GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, TRACE, HEAD and other method requests (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceTotalMethodRequestsPerSec
children.description: The rate HTTP requests using GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, TRACE or HEAD methods are made.

children.name: webserviceTotalCGIRequests
children.description: Total Common Gateway Interface (CGI) requests are custom gateway executables (.exe) the administrator can install to add forms processing or other dynamic data sources. CGI requests spawn a process on the server which can be a large drain on server resources. The count is the total since service startup.

children.name: webserviceCGIRequestsPerSec
children.description: The rate of CGI requests that are simultaneously being processed by the Web service.

children.name: webserviceTotalISAPIExtensionRequests
children.description: Total ISAPI Extension Requests are custom gateway Dynamic Link Libraries (.dll) the administrator can install to add forms processing or other dynamic data sources. Unlike CGI requests, ISAPI requests are simple calls to a DLL library routine, thus they are better suited to high performance gateway applications. The count is the total since service startup.

children.name: webserviceISAPIExtensionRequestsPerSec
children.description: The rate of ISAPI Extension requests that are simultaneously being processed by the Web service.

children.name: webserviceTotalNotFoundErrors
children.description: Total Not Found Errors is the number of requests that couldn't be satisfied by the server because the requested document could not be found. These are generally reported as an HTTP 404 error code to the client. The count is the total since service startup.

children.name: webserviceNotFoundErrorsPerSec
children.description: The rate of errors due to requests that couldn't be satisfied by the server because the requested document could not be found. These are generally reported as an HTTP 404 error code to the client.

children.name: webserviceCurrentCGIRequests
children.description: Current CGI Requests is the current number of CGI requests that are simultaneously being processed by the Web service.

children.name: webserviceCurrentISAPIExtensionRequests
children.description: Current ISAPI Extension Requests is the current number of Extension requests that are simultaneously being processed by the Web service.

children.name: webserviceMaximumCGIRequests
children.description: Maximum CGI Requests is the maximum number of CGI requests simultaneously processed by the Web service.

children.name: webserviceMaximumISAPIExtensionRequests
children.description: Maximum ISAPI Extension Requests is the maximum number of Extension requests simultaneously processed by the Web service.

children.name: webserviceTotalBlockedAsyncIPerORequests
children.description: Total requests temporarily blocked due to bandwidth throttling settings (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceTotalAllowedAsyncIPerORequests
children.description: Total requests allowed by bandwidth throttling settings (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceTotalRejectedAsyncIPerORequests
children.description: Total requests rejected due to bandwidth throttling settings (counted since service startup).

children.name: webserviceCurrentBlockedAsyncIPerORequests
children.description: Current requests temporarily blocked due to bandwidth throttling settings.

children.name: webserviceMeasuredAsyncIPerOBandwidthUsage
children.description: Measured bandwidth of asynchronous I/O averaged over a minute.

children.name: comVersionMaj
children.description: The major release version number of the software.

children.name: comVersionMin
children.description: The minor release version number of the software.

children.name: comType
children.description: The type of LAN Manager software this system is running. If no server is running the node is a workstation. This object type is an octet string of length 4 treated as a bit map (with the least significant bit being bit 0): OCTET 1 -- Software Type Bit ------------- --- workstation 0 server 1 sqlserver 2 Primary DC 3 Backup DC 4 Time Source 5 AFP Server 6 Netware Server 7 OCTET 2 -- undefined OCTET 3 -- undefined OCTET 4 -- undefined

children.name: comStatStart
children.description: The time, represented as seconds since January 1, 1970, at which the statistics on this node were last cleared.

children.name: comStatNumNetIOs
children.description: The number of network I/O operations submitted on this node.

children.name: comStatFiNetIOs
children.description: The number of network I/O operations on this node that failed issue.

children.name: comStatFcNetIOs
children.description: The number of network I/O operations on this node that failed completion.

children.name: svDescription
children.description: A comment describing this server.

children.name: svSvcNumber
children.description: The number of network services installed on this server.

children.name: svSvcTable
children.description: A list of service entries describing network services installed on this server.

children.name: svSvcEntry
children.description: The names of the network services installed on this server.

children.name: svSvcName

children.name: svSvcInstalledState

children.name: svSvcOperatingState
children.description: The operating status of the network service specified by this entry. Enumeration: 'active': 1, 'pause-pending': 3, 'paused': 4, 'continue-pending': 2.

children.name: svSvcCanBeUninstalled
children.description: Whether or not the network service specified by this entry can be uninstalled. Enumeration: 'cannot-be-uninstalled': 1, 'can-be-uninstalled': 2.

children.name: svSvcCanBePaused
children.description: Whether or not the network service specified by this entry can be paused. Enumeration: 'cannot-be-paused': 1, 'can-be-paused': 2.

children.name: svStatOpens

children.name: svStatDevOpens

children.name: svStatQueuedJobs
children.description: The total number of print jobs that have been spooled on the server.

children.name: svStatSOpens
children.description: The number of sessions that have been started on the server.

children.name: svStatErrorOuts
children.description: The number of sessions disconnected due to an error on the server.

children.name: svStatPwErrors

children.name: svStatPermErrors
children.description: The number of access permission violations encountered on this server.

children.name: svStatSysErrors
children.description: The number of system errors encountered on the server.

children.name: svStatSentBytes
children.description: The number of bytes sent by the server.

children.name: svStatRcvdBytes
children.description: The number of bytes received by this server.

children.name: svStatAvResponse
children.description: The mean number of milliseconds it has taken this server to process a workstation I/O request.

children.name: svSecurityMode
children.description: The type of security being run at this server. Enumeration: 'user-level': 2, 'share-level': 1.

children.name: svUsers
children.description: The number of concurrent users this server is able to support.

children.name: svStatReqBufsNeeded
children.description: The number of times the server has needed a request buffer in the process of handling a client request and could not allocate one.

children.name: svStatBigBufsNeeded
children.description: The number of times the server has needed a big buffer in the process of handling a client request and could not allocate one.

children.name: svSessionNumber

children.name: svSessionTable
children.description: A list of session entries corressponding to the current sessions clients have with this server.

children.name: svSessionEntry
children.description: A session that is currently established to this server.

children.name: svSesClientName
children.description: The name of the remote machine that has established the session.

children.name: svSesUserName
children.description: The name of the user at the remote machine that established the session.

children.name: svSesNumOpens
children.description: The number of open files, devices and pipes are open on this session.

children.name: svSesTime
children.description: The length of time in seconds this session has been established.

children.name: svSesIdleTime
children.description: The length of time in seconds this session has been idle.

children.name: svSesClientType
children.description: The type of client that established the session. Enumeration: 'down-level': 1, 'dos-lm': 2, 'dos-lm-2-1': 6, 'os2-lm-2': 5, 'os2-lm-1': 4, 'os2-lm-2-1': 7, 'afp-2-0': 9, 'nt-3-1': 10, 'dos-lm-2': 3, 'afp-1-1': 8.

children.name: svSesState
children.description: Used to indicate the state of this session. The deleted state will never be returned on a session but can be used in set requests to delete a session. Enumeration: 'active': 1, 'deleted': 2.

children.name: svAutoDisconnects
children.description: The number of sessions that the server has auto-disconnected due to timeout.

children.name: svDisConTime
children.description: The number of seconds the server waits before disconnecting an idle session. A value of 0xffff indicates that idle sessions will never be disconnected.

children.description: The number of jobs currently in this print queue.
